<p>
    Considering transformations of these functions has many applications. The first of which is below.
</p>



<example><title><m>b^x</m> as a Transformation of <m>e^x</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            The reason we never need a logarithm other than the natural logarithm is that an exponential function with base <m>b</m> may always be written in terms of <m>f(x) = e^x</m> as follows:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Set the two functions equal to one another with a horizontal scaling factor of <m>k</m> inside <m>e^x</m>.
                        <md>
                            b^x = e^{kx}
                        </md> 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Plug in <m>x=1</m>.
                        <md>
                            b = e^k
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Thus, we have the scaling factor <md>k=\ln(b)</md>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            We can see this at work in the following interactive.
        </p>
    <sidebyside widths="75% 25%">
                <interactive  xml:id="desmos_exp_scaling" desmos="iiq92scnk1" width="50%" aspect="5:2" />
                <image width="30%" source="exp_scaling_desmos.png"> </image>
    </sidebyside>'
    </statement>

</example>

